---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Fighting With AI">
  <style>
    .home-intro h1 {
      font-size: var(--text-3xl);
      font-weight: var(--font-bold);
      color: var(--color-text);
      margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    }

    .home-intro .lead {
      font-size: var(--text-lg);
      color: var(--color-text-muted);
      line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
      max-width: 600px;
    }

    .home-nav {
      text-align: right;
      margin-top: var(--space-8);
      padding-top: var(--space-4);
      border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
      font-size: var(--text-sm);
    }

    .home-nav a {
      color: var(--color-accent);
    }

    .home-nav a:hover {
      color: var(--color-accent-hover);
    }
  </style>

  <div class="home-intro">
    <h1>Patterns of AI Coding</h1>
    <p class="lead">AI can generate code faster than any human.</p>
    <p class="lead">It can also confidently generate the wrong code — and keep insisting it's right.</p>
    <p class="lead">The industry is reacting instead of understanding: hype on one side, rejection on the other.</p>
    <p class="lead">This site is about neither.</p>
    <p class="lead">It's a living catalog of failure modes, symptoms, and patterns for working with AI without surrendering control — so we can stop arguing about whether AI "works" and start using it intentionally.</p>

    <p class="lead">This guide is not resistance dressed up as rigor. It does not argue that AI "doesn't work," nor that it should be avoided. It documents where it works, where it breaks, and what changes when you rely on it.</p>

    <nav class="home-nav">
      <a href="/concepts/">Concepts →</a>
    </nav>
  </div>
</Layout>
